    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-12-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-12-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="429"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d429">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Council/12–2745: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the United States Representative in Bulgaria</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Barnes</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="51" xml:id="d429fn1">Sent also to Bucharest as No.
                        665.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-12-27">December 27,
                            1945—[?] p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>416. Following are sections of Moscow conference communiqué of Dec 27<note n="52"
                        xml:id="d429fn2">For full text of communiqué, see <ref
                            target="frus1945v02#pg_815">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p.
                            815</ref>; also printed in Department of State <hi rend="italic"
                            >Bulletin</hi>, December 30, 1945, p. 1027.</note> which refer to
                    Rumania and Bulgaria: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>[Here follows quotation of section V on Rumania, printed in <ref
                                target="frus1945v02#pg_821">volume II, page 821</ref>.]</p>
                        <p>VI. (<hi rend="italic">Bulgaria</hi>)</p>
                        <p>It is understood by the three governments that The Soviet Government
                            takes upon itself the mission of giving friendly advice to the Bulgarian
                            Government with regard to the desirability of the inclusion in The
                            Bulgarian Government of the fatherland front, now being formed, of an
                            additional two representatives of other democratic groups, who (<hi
                                rend="italic">a</hi>) are truly representative of the groups of the
                            parties which are not participating in the government, and (<hi
                                rend="italic">b</hi>) are really suitable and will work loyally with
                            the government.</p>
                        <p>As soon as The Governments of The United States of America and The United
                            Kingdom are convinced that this friendly advice has been accepted by The
                            Bulgarian Government and the said additional representatives have been
                            included in its body, The Government of the United States and The
                            Government of the United Kingdom will recognize The Bulgarian
                            Government, with which The Government of The Soviet Union already has
                            diplomatic relations.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
